    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm looking at my student loan amortization schedule and i'm kinda confused. i've been making my monthly payments on time every month but the principal balance is barely even going down. can you explain how the interest actually gets calculated each month? like, why does it feel like so much of my money is just disappearing instead of hitting the actual loan amount?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Loan interest is calculated monthly based on your *remaining* principal balance, meaning you pay more interest when the balance is high and less as you pay it down. Since student loans often have low interest rates compared to credit cards, most of your fixed monthly payment is technically just an interest subsidy rather than principal reduction in the early stages. This is why your balance shrinks so slowly at first, even if you are making payments perfectly on time.",
